The paper deals with algorithms for finding cuts in graphs, which is a fundamental problem in graph theory and falls under the category of distributed computing. The use of random circulations and sampling techniques suggests a connection to randomized algorithms and probability theory, which are often studied in the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The focus on cuts and connectivity also suggests a connection to the sub-category of cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). The use of linear-time sequential algorithms suggests a connection to the sub-category of cs.NA (Numerical Analysis), while the focus on graph theory and connectivity suggests a connection to the sub-category of cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Finally, the mention of faster algorithms for several problems suggests a connection to the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
